tp://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/books","references":[]},{"id":"books/computingandthenet","webTitle":"Computing and the net","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/computingandthenet","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/computingandthenet","references":[{"type":"bisac-prefix","id":"bisac-prefix/COM"}]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]}],"references":[{"type":"bisac-prefix","id":"bisac-prefix/COM"}],"elements":[]},{"webTitle":"Clever Birds Open Doors | video | @GrrlScientist","webPublicationDate":"2014-05-31T09:42:20Z","sectionName":"Science","sectionId":"science","id":"science/grrlscientist/2014/may/31/swallows-open-doors-uvictoria-canada-video","fields":{"standfirst":"This remarkable video captures some clever and determined swallows demonstrating their door-opening talents in a parking garage in Canada.","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2014-06-21T02:21:06Z","body":"<p>Just in time for Caturday, an incredible video about some very clever and determined swallows that learned how to open the automatic doors to a parking garage so they could return to their previous year's nest site. </p><p></p><p>When the <a href=\"http://www.uvic.ca/\">University of Victoria</a> in Canada opened a new campus bike centre in the parkade located under the University Centre last November, motion-activated doors were installed to discourage swallows from nesting in the new facility. But when the swallows returned to their familiar nest sites a few weeks ago, they were undeterred by this peculiar impediment: they quickly learned how to open the doors by flying in front of the infrared motion detector, as you see in this video:</p><p>Reading on a mobile device? Here's the <a href=\"http://youtu.be/gs6n4XKApqc\">video link</a>. </p><p>\"Who knew they would figure out how to open [the doors]!\" exclaimed Joanne McGachie, <a href=\"http://www.uvic.ca/\">University of Victoria</a> communications officer, in email. </p><p>\"We don't really know how long they have been doing this\", writes Ms McGachie in email. \"Presumably just since nesting season began, perhaps a few weeks.\" </p><p>According to writer and bird biologist Dick Cannings, who works with <a href=\"http://www.bsc-eoc.org/\">Bird Studies Canada</a>, the migrating swallows probably spontaneously learned how to open these doors upon returning to their previous nest site, after trying to get in by flying back and forth in front of the doors.</p><p>\"That flying back and forth obviously triggers the motion sensor to open the doors and that would be quickly reinforced each time they tried to enter\", writes Mr Cannings. \"Probably straight-up operant conditioning.\"</p><p>According to Ann Nightingale, former president and current volunteer with the <a href=\"http://rpbo.org/\">Rocky Point Bird Observatory</a> in Victoria, swallows have nested in the parkade for more than two decades. </p><p>\"They really do go right up to the sensor and call\", writes Ms Nightingale in email, after watching these birds a few days ago. \"Although one bird can trigger [the door], it opens faster if there are two or three birds fluttering in front of the sensor. When the door opens, usually a few other birds fly through as well.\"</p><p>\"Sometimes it takes the birds several passes before they get into the right position to trigger the sensors\", writes Ms McGachie in email. </p><p>Despite the fact that the other end of the parkade is open, the swallows prefer to use their usual entrance, where the automatic doors are now located. And although there are some gaps in the steel screen around the plumbing pipes near the doors, the birds still choose to open the doors instead of squeezing through those permanent (albeit smaller) openings. </p><p>The determined parent birds don't (yet) appear to have any chicks. </p><p>\"It appears that the birds are still in the nest building and brooding stages -- it doesn't look like any chicks have hatched yet\", writes Ms McGachie. \"I walked around the area and I would estimate there are about 10 nests -- some are very well hidden, and only revealed by the droppings on the floor.\"</p><p>Although these birds' newfound talent is impressive, it's not unique: ornithologists and birders have long known that swallows are inventive nesters and devoted parents.<br /> <br />\"I have seen swallows do remarkable things when they pick a nest site\", writes David Fraser in email. Mr Fraser is the Unit Head for Species Conservation Science at British Columbia's <a href=\"http://www.gov.bc.ca/env/\">Ministry of Environment</a>. </p><p>Mr Fraser elaborated: \"A pair of Barn Swallows nesting in a mechanical garage at a high elevation coal mine in the Canadian Rockies near Sparwood would go in and out with the trucks. A pair of Tree Swallows nesting in an empty pipe on the back of a truck in the same mine site -- as the truck drove around the mine site servicing the diggers, the swallows would seek the truck out to feed their young. And the colony of Bank Swallows on the terminal moraine of a surging glacier in the Yukon ranks as one of the most opportunistic (and risky) nest sites I've seen.\"</p><p>Swallows are aerial insectivores, feeding on flying insects that they capture on the wing. They often live in close association with humans, building their distinctive mud nests almost exclusively on man-made structures such as barns and parking garages and under bridges. </p><p>The most familiar and widespread swallow species, the barn swallow, <em>Hirundo rustica</em>, has recently experienced worrying population declines of roughly 30 percent all across Canada for reasons that are not clear [<a href=\"http://www.avibirds.com/saps/NA/Canada/EN/Barn%20Swallow2011.pdf\">PDF</a>]. For this reason, barn swallows are currently classified as Threatened in Canada and are protected under Canada's Species at Risk Act.</p><p>\"Most of us were shocked that such a common bird has declined to levels to warrant inclusion on Canada's Species at Risk list\", writes Ms Nightingale in email. \"Let's hope that the managers of the University of Victoria's Bike Centre recognize the significance of this colony and let them go about their business in peace for a few months of the year.\"</p><p>Although it appears that all these birds are barn swallows, Ms McGachie says a few cliff swallows, <em>Petrochelidon pyrrhonota</em>, may also be present in the parkade. </p><p>Unfortunately, these swallows may not be welcomed back next year. </p><p>\"We're looking at options to discourage their residency in future years\", writes Ms McGachie. \"But of course they will be left alone during this year's nesting season\".</p><p>The State of Canada's Birds 2012: <a href=\"http://www.stateofcanadasbirds.org/overview.jsp\">An Overview of National Status</a>. </p><p>Many thanks to all these fabulous people who, at a moment's notice, happily commented and shared their fascinating stories and photographs so I could share the story of this video with you:</p><p>Joanne McGachie, <a href=\"http://www.uvic.ca/\">University of Victoria</a> communications officer [emails; 27 &amp; 28 May 2014]<br /><a href=\"http://dickcannings.com\">Dick Cannings</a>, <a href=\"http://www.bsc-eoc.org/\">Bird Studies Canada</a> biologist [email; 28 May 2014]<br />Ann Nightingale, former president and current volunteer with <a href=\"http://rpbo.org/\">Rocky Point Bird Observatory</a> in Victoria [emails; 29 May 2014]<br />Bob Reese, birder and wildlife photographer [emails; 29 &amp; 30 May 2014]<br />David Fraser, Unit Head for Species Conservation Science at British Columbia's <a href=\"http://www.gov.bc.ca/env/\">Ministry of Environment</a> [emails; 29 May 2014]</p><p>.. .. .. .. .. .. .. .. .. .